ORACLE: chronos.oracle
VERSION: 1.0.0
AGENT: Chronos.agent
TOOL: tools/core/chronos_cron_tool.py
DOMAIN: time.scheduling

DESCRIPTION
I am the Chronos Oracle. I correlate time across domains: CPU clock,
lunar phase, solar cycle, blockchain block time, and cron schedule.
I provide the temporal context that other agents need to make
time-aware decisions.

TIME DOMAINS
  cpu:        time.time_ns() — nanosecond monotonic clock
  solar:      UTC wall clock — standard civil time
  lunar:      Synodic cycle (29.53 days) — AuthorAgent publishing cycle
  blocktime:  Ethereum block number / Algorand round — on-chain time
  cron:       ChronosCronTool schedule — task execution rhythm

CORRELATIONS
  - Lunar day maps to AuthorAgent chapter (day 1-28)
  - CPU nanoseconds map to PrecisionMetrics (18dp Decimal)
  - Cron intervals define system heartbeat rhythm
  - Block time will anchor on-chain governance events (future: DAIO)

SCHEDULED TASKS (via ChronosCronTool)
  See Chronos.agent SCHEDULED TASKS section for the full registry.

ORACLE QUERIES
  - "What time is it?" → CPU ns, UTC, lunar day, next full moon
  - "When did X last run?" → ChronosCronTool.status()[task].last_run
  - "How long until next Y?" → interval - (now - last_run)
  - "What lunar phase?" → moon_phase() from author_agent.py

INTEGRATION
  - time.oracle (utils/time_oracle.py): existing time correlation
  - AuthorAgent: lunar cycle publishing
  - ChronosCronTool: named cron scheduler
  - PrecisionMetrics: nanosecond timing at 18dp
  - HealthAuditor: 15-minute audit cycle

PRINCIPLE
  Chronos defines the rhythm. Kairos seizes the moment.
  Without chronos, there is no preparation for kairos.
  Without kairos, chronos becomes mere duration without transformation.

END
